<review>I went to Dr. Wolf for a painful chronic medical dermatology problem and was prescribed a drug which worked well.  The  prescription was automatically renewed several times without the need for an appointment.  Without warning, the pharmacy told me that the refill renewal was refused.   I called the office to ask what the problem was, and was told I would have to make an appointment.  The soonest appointment was well past the time that my medication would run out, and my condition flares up almost immediately on stopping the drug.  I asked if I could just have one more refill to hold me until the appointment, but she refused.  This is a cruel treatment of a patient. Worst physician experience anywhere in the world. Dr. Morganroth argued incessantly that the PIH on my arms was dermal. Yet, he ended up prescribing treatment (DermaSweep) and medication (Finacea) for epidermal spots despite the fact that it is well published that neither one is clinically indicated for dermal pigmentation. When I questioned his judgement, he became defensive and said he would need to conduct a biopsy. I stated that my spots were the result of injury not disease. Dr. Morganroth implied that I was not telling the truth and arrogantly asked what it was that I did for a living (which was none of his business to begin with). He became visibly upset when I responded that I have a graduate degree and made a career in management in one of the most regulated healthcare industries. While my response shut him up for a while, he continued to act in a misogynistic manner.

It is interesting that at the time of this writing, there is no record from the American Board of Plastic Surgery that Dr. Morganroth has ever been certified as a plastic surgeon. That might explain the reviews reporting serious complications following surgical procedures performed under his care. In November 2017, ironically within days after my appointment, CSI together with Dr. Morganroth and another CSI provider were named defendants in a medical malpractice lawsuit. The hearing is scheduled for early March 2018 at the Santa Clara Courthouse.<//review>

She survived being poisoned twice in Italy, the journey back to CA, & was an overall fighter. She was my first dog..the best little girl.

<Rate>5<//Rate>< review>
Our poor cat's kidney disease flared up and he was not doing well. Over a week, he stopped eating and lost his sight. He was in a lot of pain. We are grateful to have found Compassionate Heart.  The vet who came to our house explained the process beforehand so that it was clear to us. The procedure was pain-free for Snowflake.

The whole process, as heart-wrenching as it was, went smoothly. Compassionate Heart runs a great business and truly cares about helping your pet to leave this world pain-free and comfortable. The cremated remains are kept in a beautiful wooden box that they supplied, and they even made us a clay print from one of his little paws.

I highly recommend this business.<//review>

<text>Sondra was incredible.
Losing my Jake was one of the hardest things I‚Äôve ever gone through. (As it is for all of us). The few weeks prior were so difficult and the list of decisions I had to make were so overwhelming.  I had found an at home service early on in the process and then at the last minute, when it was really time, they were unavailable.  I was so nervous about having to find someone else last minute.  I was afraid it would exacerbate all of the discomfort and heartbreak I was experiencing.
Well, it was the perfect time to be reminded that things go the way they are supposed to.  I found Sondra and she was so great.  Her communication prior was honest and helpful. She was flexible with me about the timing because his situation changed last minute.  And when she arrived, I was immediately soothed by her presence.  My family spoke for weeks after about how awesome she was.
She has the most incredible balance. She is calming with her clear language and tone and yet has a still and compassionate energy that  gives you and your family the space to fully experience your emotions.   She was gentle yet demonstrated method and confidence in the procedure she was performing. Her presence was fully supportive without any over dramatizing, which I very much appreciate.
After he passed, my family went outside and I stayed to finish the process with her.  I was happier with just her and I in the room than I would have been with even my loved ones at that time. I have so much deep appreciation for who she is and that she was the one there for me and us in that very difficult moment.  I will forever choose at home euthanasia for any pet I own, and I hope I will still be able to find her when that time comes.<//text>< response>

< Review>
It's taken me a few months to be able to write this, but Sondra came to my home on short notice on a Friday night last December when my sweet kitty was fading quickly.

She actually had a seizure within minutes of Sondra's arrival and she was able to act swiftly to give her an injection that allowed her to relax immediately. She went right to work to ensure her passing was painless. She was kind and gentle, and so considerate of my feelings. Careful to explain what she was doing, not rushing me in any way. She patiently allowed me to be as involved as I desired, let the other animals in my home take their time with her, and let me take my time saying goodbye.

This was one of the hardest scenarios I've faced, but being able to do so at home, rather than the cold, institutional setting of a vet office was worth it all. I know that this is the route I will take in the future for my pets, so that they can be comfortable, instead of stressed, when it's time for them to cross the rainbow bridge.< /Review>

<Pics>None< /Pics><Review>Sasha was diagnosed with lymphoma in February.  Shortly after, I contacted Sondra who spent at least 45 minutes with me on the phone.  During the course of Sasha losing her battle with cancer, I remained in contact with Sondra and she was always very kind and supportive. I even sent her a video of how Sasha was doing. As Sasha's time came closer I reluctantly scheduled a time for Sondra to come out - Monday May 16th. But the night before our girl was outside, circling the hot tub chasing a mouse. Her breathing had been shallow & her appetite had tapered off, but she still had so much energy. We couldn't do it, we weren't ready. I called Sondra and informed her of our decision to cancel.  She never pressured us at any point during this difficult time. Monday came, I went to work but had received a call from my wife that Sasha was not doing well. Before leaving work I called Sondra and told her about Sasha taking a turn for the worse.  She asked if 7:30 at night would work and I agreed. I left work early, came home and noticed our girl was not well at all, a sudden & drastic decline from the previous night. So once home around noon, I called again and asked if she could come sooner.  Sondra was at  North County home within 2 hrs from my call. I lied on the floor next to my dog until she arrived. She came in and immediately sat on the floor next to me & my dog. She comforted Sasha while she spoke to us. Kind, caring. This is not a job for Sondra, this is her passion. She truly cares, she gets it, she understands. I couldn't have asked for a more peaceful passing. I cried, a lot - but couldn't have asked for a better person to be there with us.  I requested she bring an ink pad for a tattoo I want of her paw print, she also provides a nice clay impression. My only regret is not giving Sondra more of a hug - that was only to keep me from crying more.  It was a hard decision to make, it sucks, it's sad. Although knowing this & how I feel, I know we will get another dog someday. I love them too much not to have one. Thank you Sondra

</record></dataset><record>
<username>Toasty Yoshi</username><rating>3< /rating>< Text>
There are pros and cons for this gym. I have a membership for three years for around $9 per month, so it isn't a bad price. This also includes another person coming with me for free every time, and there are no other fees that I need to pay. It was also easy for me to signup and I could pay the entire amount up-front, unlike similarly priced gyms.

Along with the pros above, there are cons: this place tends to lack cleaning supplies, so I've had to begin bringing my own with me every time now. The bathrooms are also filthy, but I've just come to accept that it's a common occurrence at most gyms nowadays--especially in California. Half the time, nobody is at the front desk, so people sneak in a lot. I've seen it happen three times already, and was stunned that they weren't seen. It also can sometimes be extremely hot and stuffy downstairs, so it'd be nice if they invested in some large, industrial fans for the rooms. One last thing that may not matter to others as much as it does to me: this place closes way too early and opens way too late on weekends. I like to get my workouts done throughout the week and the weekends, and I'm usually working late on studies into the night. I wish they opened at 5 A.M. on weekends like they do during the weekdays.< /Text>

5< /Rating>
< Text>
Our home was built in 1923. Over the years it's had many owners and was maintained fairly well but not consistently. My hubby and I bought the home three years ago. We had big dreams of doing renovations and over the covid -19 quarantine decided to take advantage of the time at home. We were stuck there anyway and it made a lot of sense. However, once we got to the exterior after the siding was done we realized how poorly our roof reflected the amount of money and time we put into the home. Around the time we finished our siding, we received a letter from American Home Energy Savers referring to some of the rebates available for energy efficiency upgrades which included roof replacement and HVAC upgrades. Our roof was old and definitely needed to be replaced in contrast to the new siding. It looked terrible. We called and booked an appointment with a technician. Steve, our technician took us through the process of what we would encounter if we chose to proceed with the pace funding program and energy efficiency rebates. He took some time to go up into our attic on our roof and to correctly assess the project scope. We invited other contractors to visit the house. No one else had taken as much time to ensure that our final quote was accurate. After Steve's visit, we met with Jaime, an advisor who walked us through the entire process. He provided us with accurate pricing and a quick turnaround. Our financing was approved on the spot while we talked with him at our dining room table. (masked up but still able to talk face to face) We were super surprised that within a month, we had a new roof, a new HVAC unit on our roof with dual stage electric functionality. Our energy bills have decreased and our roof looks amazing. Because American Home Energy Savers is a general contractor we were also able to tackle another project. Our porch needed to be reinforced. They were able to do that for us. We are super happy with the experience. We had a couple of small minor issues that they immediately remedied.

10 out of 10 would recommend again.< /Text>

<userid>107659438865581575585</userid><user_name>Mark Uuskallio</user_name><Resp>None< /Resp><rate>5</rate>< text>
The LA store gets five stars, HOWEVER, Ninebot Segway is another story. The price was the best on the store's web site at the time I wanted to buy two G30 Max scooters. I ordered them with no issues after a friendly talk with a store clerk at the Brick and Mortar Store in LA. A week later my wife and I were unpacking our new toys. I was able to follow the directions, load the app on my phone and connect the G30 to my phone through the app without paying much attention, nice! My wife noticed that the G30 she was working with seemed to have been out of the box before. When we got to the Bluetooth pairing part there was no blinking Bluetooth light on the dashboard of the G30 and it would not connect with my wife's phone. The manual reads that there should be a blinking blue light with the Bluetooth icon and when we called tech service they said the same thing and that the main control board was the issue. We sent the G30 back and got a replacement two weeks later. Set up went the same way, no Bluetooth light. Tech service agent said we would have to send it back, AGAIN!
Just for giggles I called the LA store. The clerk was super nice. He fired up a G30 on the store floor and said there is no blinking light on G30's. then he said to try connecting it to my phone and it connected right away!
The issue was with my wife's phone, Tech service insisted it was a control board issue if there was no light blinking and the Ninebot manual clearly states there should be a Bluetooth Icon blinking during the pairing phase, NOT.
I sent a note back to Tech service and the store about the issue, the clerk thanked me, tech service was unresponsive. What a hassle! Horrible Tech service and bad manuals.
The G30's are a blast to ride! We enjoy taking them to cities and towns to explore new areas. We giggle and laugh the whole time we ride! Two 60+ year old kids!< /text>

<review>I used them for the first time recently for an inside, outside and engine detail in order to get my older car ready to be sold. They exceeded all my expectations! < Review>
I've never had an issue whenever I stop by this or any of the surrounding Best Buy stores. They always have a great variety of items from your basic computers cables to dedicated graphics cards, monitors, hard drives, and everything in between. Recently I had an excellent experience with their Customer Service team and wanted to leave a note about it. I wanted to return a computer monitor I purchased from a different Best Buy store so I could upgrade to a 144hz 2k monitor.

When I bought the monitor, I thought I still had my Best Buy Elite Plus benefits which includes a 45-day return policy. However, when I bought this monitor I did not realize that my benefits had elapsed, which meant that I only had a 15-day return policy and I didn't not realize that I was past the return period until I was at the store trying to return the monitor.

To keep the story short, the store associate reached out to his manager and was able to receive approval to process a full return (because they did not have a 144hz 2k monitor available). Even though he had every right to simply cite store policy and deny the return outright. It's little experiences like these that keep me coming back to Best Buy for all my minor and major purchases.

Now I have to work my way back up through the rewards system to regain my Best Buy Elite Plus benefits!<//Review>

<rate>1< /rate>< Review>
If you are convinced that the word "Geek" will automatically ensure a safe transfer of your life's data from one laptop to another, think again. Not only was said "geek" unable to transfer my data, but he/she reformatted my extracted hard drive to be incompatible with a Mac OS System. Mind you, I gave the "geek" this hard drive with a newly purchased Macbook Pro, shiny and brand spankin' new like a baby's bottom.

The past six years of data that was stored on that hard drive is gone. Irreplaceable and unable to be found. Incompatible, as they say, with anything and everything I try to plug it into. Docks and floods and plugs,  you name it.

So, to all of you who are in a rush (as I was) to save yourself and your data, take a breathe, eat a piece of chocolate, and really think about who you are handing your "babies" over to. Not everyone who is shielded by words like "data technician," "total tech support," horn-rimmed glasses and the word "geek" on their name tag is as helpful as you may think.<//Review>
